# Single-cell sQTL workflow (2-stage): junction calling 



## Getting Started 

### Prerequisites

python3, awk, cut

### Dependency

htslib 1.3 (https://github.com/samtools/htslib/archive/refs/tags/1.3.tar.gz)

```
mkdir -p ~/software 
cd ~/software
wget https://github.com/samtools/htslib/archive/refs/tags/1.3.tar.gz

tar -xzvf 1.3.tar.gz
cd htslib-1.3
autoreconf -i 
INSTALL_DIR="$HOME/software/htslib-1.3"
./configure --prefix="$INSTALL_DIR"
make
make install
```

Add the library directory to $LD_LIBRARY_PATH. 

```
export LD_LIBRARY_PATH="$INSTALL_DIR/lib:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH"
```

### Installing

Two more tools to be installed 

```
cd ~/software
git clone https://github.com/tibettiger/Junctions_quantification 
git clone https://github.com/davidaknowles/leafcutter
```

Add junctools to $PATH (for example, under ~/bin/). 

```
mkdir -p ~/bin
cp Junctions_quantification/junctools ~/bin/
chmod 744 ~/bin/junctools 
export PATH=~/bin:$PATH
```

Please test the software before proceeding to the pipeline. 



## Overview of the junction calling pipeline

1. Extract intron junction information from indexed BAM files (e.g. possorted_genome_bam.bam output by Cell Ranger, with index file possorted_genome_bam.bam.bai) 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This step works by labelling each junction with cell barcode (CB) and Unique molecular identifier (UMI). 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Runtime and peak RAM for a ~40G BAM is ~1h and ~100 GB, respectively. A typical output file: [junction file](https://github.com/boxiangliulab/sc-sQTLgen-consortium/blob/main/example/OneK1K.pool_1.junc_barcoded). 

2. Prepare pseudo-bulk junction files (one per individual, per cell type) 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This step extracts individual-level cell-type-specific junctions. Pattern for name of files: [individual_celltype.junc]

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Runtime is within ~5m. The pseudo-bulk junction files are generated with individual and cell type information for each cell: [meta file](https://github.com/boxiangliulab/sc-sQTLgen-consortium/blob/main/example/OneK1K.metadata.pool_1.txt). 

3. Cluster intron junctions (one file per cell type) 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This step integrates junction information from all individuals for each cell type. 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;An example output file (OneK1K_cluster.CD4_NC_perind.counts.gz) looks like this:

## Defining the variables

Define global variables including output directory and the name of your cohort.

```
outDir=/data/project/sc_sQTLGen/junction_calling/output
cohort=OneK1K
```

For each BAM file, an easy-to-read identifier is set for the name of junction file. 

```
bamFile=/data/project/sc_sQTLGen/junction_calling/input/GSM5899873/possorted_genome_bam.bam
id=pool_1
```

For each junction file (each from one BAM), a meta data file is required ([sample metadata](https://github.com/boxiangliulab/sc-sQTLgen-consortium/blob/main/example/OneK1K.metadata.pool_1.txt)). The two columns are barcode and individual_celltype. 

```
id=pool_1 
meta=/data/project/sc_sQTLGen/junction_calling/input/GSM5899873/OneK1K.metadata.pool_1.txt
```

For each cell type, \${ct} is defined as meta data. 

```
ct="CD4_NC"
```



## Running the pipeline

Please run the first two steps for all the bam files firstly, and then run the third step for each cell type. 

### Extract intron junctions from BAM files 

*Of note, this step requires a large amount of RAM when processing large BAM files (refer to #1 in the above section).*

```
mkdir -p ${outDir}/junc/
junctools junctions extract -a 8 -m 50 -M 500000 \
         -s RF ${bamFile} -o ${outDir}/junc/${id}.junc_barcoded
```

### Prepare pseudo-bulk junction files (per cell type, per individual)

```
junc=${outDir}/junc/${id}.junc_barcoded
mkdir -p ${outDir}/pseudobulk_junc

# Use awk to process the main file and split into groups
awk -F'\t' -v meta="${meta}" -v outDir="${outDir}" '
    BEGIN {
        while ((getline < meta) > 0) {
            BC = gensub(/-[0-9]+$/, "", "1", $1)
            groups[BC] = $2
        }
        close(meta)
    }
    {
        key = gensub(/-[0-9]+$/, "", "1", $13)
        if (key in groups) {
            group_file = outDir "/pseudobulk_junc/" groups[key] ".junc.tmp"
            print $0 >> group_file
        } else {
            print "No group found for " key
        }
    }
' "${junc}"
```

Run this manually after all jobs complete 

```
cd ${outDir}/pseudobulk_junc
for tmp_file in *.tmp; do
    final_file=$(basename "$tmp_file" .tmp)
    mv "$tmp_file" "$final_file"
done
```

### Cluster intron junctions

```
mkdir -p ${outDir}/pseudobulk_junc_format/${ct}/
ls ${outDir}/pseudobulk_junc/*${ct}.junc | while read i 
do
    newname=`basename $i |  sed 's/\([0-9]*_[0-9]*\).*/\1/'`
    cut -f1-12 $i > ${outDir}/pseudobulk_junc_format/${ct}/${newname}.junc
done


ls ${outDir}/pseudobulk_junc_format/${ct}/*.junc > ${outDir}/pseudobulk_junc_format/juncfiles.${ct}.txt

mkdir -p ${outDir}/cluster/${ct}
cd ${outDir}/cluster/${ct} 
python ~/software/leafcutter/clustering/leafcutter_cluster_regtools.py -j ${outDir}/pseudobulk_junc_format/juncfiles.${ct}.txt \
       -m 0 -p 0 -l 500000 -o ${cohort}_cluster.${ct}
```



## Output

Send output count file to central analysis for joint junction quality control & filtering: 

\${cohort}_cluster.\${ct}_perind.counts.gz
